Abstraction in C++

Abstraction means showing only important details and hiding implementation details from the user.

ðŸ‘‰ In simple words:
What to do is shown, how it is done is hidden.

ðŸ”¸ How Abstraction is Achieved in C++

Abstraction in C++ is mainly achieved using:

Abstract Classes

Interfaces (using pure virtual functions)

ðŸ”¹ 1. Abstract Class

A class that contains at least one pure virtual function is called an abstract class.

ðŸ”¸ Pure Virtual Function
virtual void functionName() = 0;

âœ… Example
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Shape {   // Abstract class
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;   // Pure virtual function
};

class Circle : public Shape {
public:
    void draw() {
        cout << "Drawing Circle";
    }
};

int main() {
    Shape* s;
    Circle c;
    s = &c;
    s->draw();
}

ðŸ§  Explanation

Shape defines what to do (draw)

Circle defines how to do it

User only interacts with Shape

ðŸ”¹ 2. Interface in C++ (Concept)

C++ doesnâ€™t have a keyword interface like Java,
but we can simulate interfaces using only pure virtual functions.

âœ… Example
class Vehicle {
public:
    virtual void start() = 0;
    virtual void stop() = 0;
};

ðŸ”¸ Real-Life Example

ATM Machine

User sees: Withdraw, Deposit, Balance

User doesnâ€™t see: Bank server logic

ðŸ”¹ Advantages of Abstraction

âœ” Reduces complexity
âœ” Improves security
âœ” Helps in code reusability
âœ” Easier maintenance

ðŸ”¹| Feature        | **Abstraction**                  | **Encapsulation**                                    |
| -------------- | -------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| Meaning        | Hides **implementation details** | Hides **data (variables)**                           |
| Focus          | **What** an object can do        | **How** data is protected                            |
| Purpose        | Reduce complexity                | Protect data                                         |
| Achieved using | Abstract classes, interfaces     | Access specifiers (`private`, `protected`, `public`) |
| Level          | Design level                     | Implementation level                                 |
| Example        | `virtual void draw() = 0;`       | `private int balance;`                               |
